                        "@aii:was-generated-by": "http://data.elsevier.com/art/structure-references art:version v2.0.229",
                        "ref-fulltext": "4 For a good overview of the initial successful NPI approach of Thailand as a country to the pandemic and the later mistakes that brought about the third wave, see Kumthorn Malathum and Porntip Malathum, \u2018The covid-19 Pandemic: What we have learned from Thai experiences\u2019, Pacific Rim International Journal of Nursing Research 24, no. 4 (2020): 431-435; and Henning Glaser \u2018Thailand\u2019s Covid-19 Struggle: Conditions, Consequences, Revelations\u2019, Asia Fighting Covid-19 paper series (Bangkok: Thammasat University, 2021): 1-19. The latter author observes that the excellent voluntary compliance with NPIs among the Thais \u2018is largely the result of public morality that places importance on the\u2026 avoidance of putting others at risk.\u2019 (p. 6). In the latter part of 2021, however, mainly due to the slow rollout of the vaccination, the epidemic situation significantly deteriorated. Thus, although Thailand can still be counted as one of the successful countries that managed to save proportionally almost ten times more lives than some of the worst-performing countries such as the U.S. or the Czech Republic, some metrics rank it relatively low. For instance, \u2018Thailand\u2019s rank in the Nikkei COVID-19 Recovery Index, which ranks more than 120 countries on their recovery chances as derived from data on infection management, vaccine rollout, and social mobility\u2026 [was]\u2026 almost last of all recorded countries globally at a devastating position of 119, one rank after Zambia (118) and one before the two countries listed last, Namibia and South Africa (both 120)\u2019. (p. 8). For Zambia and its initial success, see David Mutemwa, Veronika Zvanovcova, Anna Helova, and Daniel D. Novotny. \u2018The Role of Religion, Philosophy of Life, Global Health, Traditional Medicine, and Past Experiences in the Covid-19 Pandemic Response: Zambia Case Study.\u2019 Caritas et Veritas 11, no. 1 (2021): 18-49; needless to say, in the case of Africa, unlike that of Thailand, we have not much certainty when it comes to statistics, see also Joseph Waogodo Cabore et al., \u2018COVID-19 in the 47 countries of the WHO African region: a modelling analysis of past trends and future patterns\u2019, Lancet Glob Health Jun 1 (2022): S2214-109X(22)00233-9. For Thailand\u2019s overall top pandemic preparedness (including its surveillance, containment, response), see detailed reports of the John Hopkins Health Security Index that ranked Thailand #6 (2019) and #5 (2021) worldwide. For a commentary on Thailand\u2019s evaluation in the index, see Alwin Issac et al., \u2018An examination of Thailand\u2019s health care system and strategies during the management of the COVID-19 pandemic\u2019, Journal of global health, 11:03002, (2021).",
